<Layout title="Econ Ch.23 — Comparative Systems" favicon="💰">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/economics/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to economics</a>

    <h1>Comparative Systems</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Sources: Wikipedia (CC BY-SA 4.0) · Adam Smith, <em>Wealth of Nations</em> (1776, public domain) · F.A. Hayek, "The Use of Knowledge in Society" (1945)</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Markets and central planning are two answers to the same question: how to coordinate production when knowledge is distributed. <strong>Hayek's insight</strong>: prices are a communication protocol. They aggregate dispersed local knowledge into a signal that no single planner could compute.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Hayek's Knowledge Problem -->
    <h3>The knowledge problem</h3>
    <p>Hayek's 1945 argument: the economic problem is not how to allocate resources given complete knowledge, but how to use knowledge that is <strong>dispersed</strong> across millions of people, much of it tacit (knowledge of "the particular circumstances of time and place"). A central planner cannot collect this knowledge fast enough. Prices solve this by compressing local information into a single number that everyone can act on.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Decentralized vs Centralized networks -->
